689 /*************************************************************************
690 This structure stores optimization report:
691 * IterationsCount number of iterations
692 * NFEV number of gradient evaluations
693 * TerminationType termination type (see below)
694 
695 TERMINATION CODES
696 
697 TerminationType field contains completion code, which can be:
698  -7 gradient verification failed.
699  See MinBLEICSetGradientCheck() for more information.
700  -3 inconsistent constraints. Feasible point is
701  either nonexistent or too hard to find. Try to
702  restart optimizer with better initial approximation
703  1 relative function improvement is no more than EpsF.
704  2 relative step is no more than EpsX.
705  4 gradient norm is no more than EpsG
706  5 MaxIts steps was taken
707  7 stopping conditions are too stringent,
708  further improvement is impossible,
709  X contains best point found so far.
710 
711 ADDITIONAL FIELDS
712 
713 There are additional fields which can be used for debugging:
714 * DebugEqErr error in the equality constraints (2-norm)
715 * DebugFS f, calculated at projection of initial point
716  to the feasible set
717 * DebugFF f, calculated at the final point
718 * DebugDX |X_start-X_final|
719 *************************************************************************/
720 class _minbleicreport_owner
721 {
722 public:
723  _minbleicreport_owner();
724  _minbleicreport_owner(const _minbleicreport_owner &rhs);
725  _minbleicreport_owner& operator=(const _minbleicreport_owner &rhs);
726  virtual ~_minbleicreport_owner();
727  alglib_impl::minbleicreport* c_ptr();
728  alglib_impl::minbleicreport* c_ptr() const;
729 protected:
730  alglib_impl::minbleicreport *p_struct;
731 };

1060 
1061 /*************************************************************************
1062  NONLINEAR CONJUGATE GRADIENT METHOD
1063 
1064 DESCRIPTION:
1065 The subroutine minimizes function F(x) of N arguments by using one of the
1066 nonlinear conjugate gradient methods.
1067 
1068 These CG methods are globally convergent (even on non-convex functions) as
1069 long as grad(f) is Lipschitz continuous in a some neighborhood of the
1070 L = { x : f(x)<=f(x0) }.
1071 
1072 
1073 REQUIREMENTS:
1074 Algorithm will request following information during its operation:
1075 * function value F and its gradient G (simultaneously) at given point X
1076 
1077 
1078 USAGE:
1079 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinCGCreate() call
1080 2. User tunes solver parameters with MinCGSetCond(), MinCGSetStpMax() and
1081  other functions
1082 3. User calls MinCGOptimize() function which takes algorithm state and
1083  pointer (delegate, etc.) to callback function which calculates F/G.
1084 4. User calls MinCGResults() to get solution
1085 5. Optionally, user may call MinCGRestartFrom() to solve another problem
1086  with same N but another starting point and/or another function.
1087  MinCGRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized structure.
1088 
1089 
1090 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1091  N - problem dimension, N>0:
1092  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
1093  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
1094  X - starting point, array[0..N-1].
1095 
1096 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
1097  State - structure which stores algorithm state
1098 
1099  -- ALGLIB --
1100  Copyright 25.03.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1101 *************************************************************************/
1102 void mincgcreate(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, mincgstate &state);
1103 void mincgcreate(const real_1d_array &x, mincgstate &state);
1104 
1105 
1106 /*************************************************************************
1107 The subroutine is finite difference variant of MinCGCreate(). It uses
1108 finite differences in order to differentiate target function.
1109 
1110 Description below contains information which is specific to this function
1111 only. We recommend to read comments on MinCGCreate() in order to get more
1112 information about creation of CG optimizer.
1113 
1114 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1115  N - problem dimension, N>0:
1116  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
1117  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
1118  X - starting point, array[0..N-1].
1119  DiffStep- differentiation step, >0
1120 
1121 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
1122  State - structure which stores algorithm state
1123 
1124 NOTES:
1125 1. algorithm uses 4-point central formula for differentiation.
1126 2. differentiation step along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I] where
1127  S[] is scaling vector which can be set by MinCGSetScale() call.
1128 3. we recommend you to use moderate values of differentiation step. Too
1129  large step will result in too large truncation errors, while too small
1130  step will result in too large numerical errors. 1.0E-6 can be good
1131  value to start with.
1132 4. Numerical differentiation is very inefficient - one gradient
1133  calculation needs 4*N function evaluations. This function will work for
1134  any N - either small (1...10), moderate (10...100) or large (100...).
1135  However, performance penalty will be too severe for any N's except for
1136  small ones.
1137  We should also say that code which relies on numerical differentiation
1138  is less robust and precise. L-BFGS needs exact gradient values.
1139  Imprecise gradient may slow down convergence, especially on highly
1140  nonlinear problems.
1141  Thus we recommend to use this function for fast prototyping on small-
1142  dimensional problems only, and to implement analytical gradient as soon
1143  as possible.
1144 
1145  -- ALGLIB --
1146  Copyright 16.05.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
1147 *************************************************************************/
1148 void mincgcreatef(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, mincgstate &state);
1149 void mincgcreatef(const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, mincgstate &state);
1150 
1151 
1152 /*************************************************************************
1153 This function sets stopping conditions for CG optimization algorithm.
1154 
1155 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1156  State - structure which stores algorithm state
1157  EpsG - >=0
1158  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
1159  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
1160  * |.| means Euclidian norm
1161  * v - scaled gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
1162  * g - gradient
1163  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinCGSetScale()
1164  EpsF - >=0
1165  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
1166  the condition |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
1167  is satisfied.
1168  EpsX - >=0
1169  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
1170  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
1171  * |.| means Euclidian norm
1172  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
1173  * dx - ste pvector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
1174  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinCGSetScale()
1175  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
1176  iterations is unlimited.
1177 
1178 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0, EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead to
1179 automatic stopping criterion selection (small EpsX).
1180 
1181  -- ALGLIB --
1182  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1183 *************************************************************************/
1184 void mincgsetcond(const mincgstate &state, const double epsg, const double epsf, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits);
1185 
1186 
1187 /*************************************************************************
1188 This function sets scaling coefficients for CG optimizer.
1189 
1190 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
1191 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
1192 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
1193 a) "how large" the variable is
1194 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
1195 
1196 Scaling is also used by finite difference variant of CG optimizer - step
1197 along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I].
1198 
1199 In most optimizers (and in the CG too) scaling is NOT a form of
1200 preconditioning. It just affects stopping conditions. You should set
1201 preconditioner by separate call to one of the MinCGSetPrec...() functions.
1202 
1203 There is special preconditioning mode, however, which uses scaling
1204 coefficients to form diagonal preconditioning matrix. You can turn this
1205 mode on, if you want. But you should understand that scaling is not the
1206 same thing as preconditioning - these are two different, although related
1207 forms of tuning solver.
1208 
1209 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1210  State - structure stores algorithm state
1211  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
1212  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
1213 
1214  -- ALGLIB --
1215  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
1216 *************************************************************************/
1217 void mincgsetscale(const mincgstate &state, const real_1d_array &s);

1272 /*************************************************************************
1273 This function allows to suggest initial step length to the CG algorithm.
1274 
1275 Suggested step length is used as starting point for the line search. It
1276 can be useful when you have badly scaled problem, i.e. when ||grad||
1277 (which is used as initial estimate for the first step) is many orders of
1278 magnitude different from the desired step.
1279 
1280 Line search may fail on such problems without good estimate of initial
1281 step length. Imagine, for example, problem with ||grad||=10^50 and desired
1282 step equal to 0.1 Line search function will use 10^50 as initial step,
1283 then it will decrease step length by 2 (up to 20 attempts) and will get
1284 10^44, which is still too large.
1285 
1286 This function allows us to tell than line search should be started from
1287 some moderate step length, like 1.0, so algorithm will be able to detect
1288 desired step length in a several searches.
1289 
1290 Default behavior (when no step is suggested) is to use preconditioner, if
1291 it is available, to generate initial estimate of step length.
1292 
1293 This function influences only first iteration of algorithm. It should be
1294 called between MinCGCreate/MinCGRestartFrom() call and MinCGOptimize call.
1295 Suggested step is ignored if you have preconditioner.
1296 
1297 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1298  State - structure used to store algorithm state.
1299  Stp - initial estimate of the step length.
1300  Can be zero (no estimate).
1301 
1302  -- ALGLIB --
1303  Copyright 30.07.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1304 *************************************************************************/
1305 void mincgsuggeststep(const mincgstate &state, const double stp);

1380 /*************************************************************************
1381 This family of functions is used to launcn iterations of nonlinear optimizer
1382 
1383 These functions accept following parameters:
1384  state - algorithm state
1385  func - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
1386  value func at given point x
1387  grad - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
1388  value func and gradient grad at given point x
1389  rep - optional callback which is called after each iteration
1390  can be NULL
1391  ptr - optional pointer which is passed to func/grad/hess/jac/rep
1392  can be NULL
1393 
1394 NOTES:
1395 
1396 1. This function has two different implementations: one which uses exact
1397  (analytical) user-supplied gradient, and one which uses function value

1501 /*************************************************************************
1502 
1503 This subroutine turns on verification of the user-supplied analytic
1504 gradient:
1505 * user calls this subroutine before optimization begins
1506 * MinCGOptimize() is called
1507 * prior to actual optimization, for each component of parameters being
1508  optimized X[i] algorithm performs following steps:
1509  * two trial steps are made to X[i]-TestStep*S[i] and X[i]+TestStep*S[i],
1510  where X[i] is i-th component of the initial point and S[i] is a scale
1511  of i-th parameter
1512  * F(X) is evaluated at these trial points
1513  * we perform one more evaluation in the middle point of the interval
1514  * we build cubic model using function values and derivatives at trial
1515  points and we compare its prediction with actual value in the middle
1516  point
1517  * in case difference between prediction and actual value is higher than
1518  some predetermined threshold, algorithm stops with completion code -7;
1519  Rep.VarIdx is set to index of the parameter with incorrect derivative.
1520 * after verification is over, algorithm proceeds to the actual optimization.
1521 
1522 NOTE 1: verification needs N (parameters count) gradient evaluations. It
1523  is very costly and you should use it only for low dimensional
1524  problems, when you want to be sure that you've correctly
1525  calculated analytic derivatives. You should not use it in the
1526  production code (unless you want to check derivatives provided by
1527  some third party).
1528 
1529 NOTE 2: you should carefully choose TestStep. Value which is too large
1530  (so large that function behaviour is significantly non-cubic) will
1531  lead to false alarms. You may use different step for different
1532  parameters by means of setting scale with MinCGSetScale().
1533 
1534 NOTE 3: this function may lead to false positives. In case it reports that
1535  I-th derivative was calculated incorrectly, you may decrease test
1536  step and try one more time - maybe your function changes too
1537  sharply and your step is too large for such rapidly chanding
1538  function.
1539 
1540 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1541  State - structure used to store algorithm state
1542  TestStep - verification step:
1543  * TestStep=0 turns verification off
1544  * TestStep>0 activates verification
1545 
1546  -- ALGLIB --
1547  Copyright 31.05.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
1548 *************************************************************************/
1549 void mincgsetgradientcheck(const mincgstate &state, const double teststep);

1551 /*************************************************************************
1552  BOUND CONSTRAINED OPTIMIZATION
1553  WITH ADDITIONAL LINEAR EQUALITY AND INEQUALITY CONSTRAINTS
1554 
1555 DESCRIPTION:
1556 The subroutine minimizes function F(x) of N arguments subject to any
1557 combination of:
1558 * bound constraints
1559 * linear inequality constraints
1560 * linear equality constraints
1561 
1562 REQUIREMENTS:
1563 * user must provide function value and gradient
1564 * starting point X0 must be feasible or
1565  not too far away from the feasible set
1566 * grad(f) must be Lipschitz continuous on a level set:
1567  L = { x : f(x)<=f(x0) }
1568 * function must be defined everywhere on the feasible set F
1569 
1570 USAGE:
1571 
1572 Constrained optimization if far more complex than the unconstrained one.
1573 Here we give very brief outline of the BLEIC optimizer. We strongly recommend
1574 you to read examples in the ALGLIB Reference Manual and to read ALGLIB User Guide
1575 on optimization, which is available at http://www.alglib.net/optimization/
1576 
1577 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinBLEICCreate() call
1578 
1579 2. USer adds boundary and/or linear constraints by calling
1580  MinBLEICSetBC() and MinBLEICSetLC() functions.
1581 
1582 3. User sets stopping conditions with MinBLEICSetCond().
1583 
1584 4. User calls MinBLEICOptimize() function which takes algorithm state and
1585  pointer (delegate, etc.) to callback function which calculates F/G.
1586 
1587 5. User calls MinBLEICResults() to get solution
1588 
1589 6. Optionally user may call MinBLEICRestartFrom() to solve another problem
1590  with same N but another starting point.
1591  MinBLEICRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized structure.
1592 
1593 
1594 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1595  N - problem dimension, N>0:
1596  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
1597  * if not given, automatically determined from size ofX
1598  X - starting point, array[N]:
1599  * it is better to set X to a feasible point
1600  * but X can be infeasible, in which case algorithm will try
1601  to find feasible point first, using X as initial
1602  approximation.
1603 
1604 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
1605  State - structure stores algorithm state
1606 
1607  -- ALGLIB --
1608  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1609 *************************************************************************/
1610 void minbleiccreate(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, minbleicstate &state);

1614 /*************************************************************************
1615 The subroutine is finite difference variant of MinBLEICCreate(). It uses
1616 finite differences in order to differentiate target function.
1617 
1618 Description below contains information which is specific to this function
1619 only. We recommend to read comments on MinBLEICCreate() in order to get
1620 more information about creation of BLEIC optimizer.
1621 
1622 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1623  N - problem dimension, N>0:
1624  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
1625  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
1626  X - starting point, array[0..N-1].
1627  DiffStep- differentiation step, >0
1628 
1629 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
1630  State - structure which stores algorithm state
1631 
1632 NOTES:
1633 1. algorithm uses 4-point central formula for differentiation.
1634 2. differentiation step along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I] where
1635  S[] is scaling vector which can be set by MinBLEICSetScale() call.
1636 3. we recommend you to use moderate values of differentiation step. Too
1637  large step will result in too large truncation errors, while too small
1638  step will result in too large numerical errors. 1.0E-6 can be good
1639  value to start with.
1640 4. Numerical differentiation is very inefficient - one gradient
1641  calculation needs 4*N function evaluations. This function will work for
1642  any N - either small (1...10), moderate (10...100) or large (100...).
1643  However, performance penalty will be too severe for any N's except for
1644  small ones.
1645  We should also say that code which relies on numerical differentiation
1646  is less robust and precise. CG needs exact gradient values. Imprecise
1647  gradient may slow down convergence, especially on highly nonlinear
1648  problems.
1649  Thus we recommend to use this function for fast prototyping on small-
1650  dimensional problems only, and to implement analytical gradient as soon
1651  as possible.
1652 
1653  -- ALGLIB --
1654  Copyright 16.05.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
1655 *************************************************************************/

1660 /*************************************************************************
1661 This function sets boundary constraints for BLEIC optimizer.
1662 
1663 Boundary constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation).
1664 They are preserved after algorithm restart with MinBLEICRestartFrom().
1665 
1666 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1667  State - structure stores algorithm state

1669  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
1670  very small number or -INF.
1671  BndU - upper bounds, array[N].
1672  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
1673  very large number or +INF.

1676 variable will be "frozen" at X[i]=BndL[i]=BndU[i].

1690 /*************************************************************************
1691 This function sets linear constraints for BLEIC optimizer.
1692 
1693 Linear constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation).
1694 They are preserved after algorithm restart with MinBLEICRestartFrom().
1695 
1696 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1697  State - structure previously allocated with MinBLEICCreate call.
1698  C - linear constraints, array[K,N+1].
1699  Each row of C represents one constraint, either equality
1700  or inequality (see below):
1701  * first N elements correspond to coefficients,
1702  * last element corresponds to the right part.
1703  All elements of C (including right part) must be finite.
1704  CT - type of constraints, array[K]:
1705  * if CT[i]>0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x >= C[i,n+1]
1706  * if CT[i]=0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x = C[i,n+1]
1707  * if CT[i]<0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x <= C[i,n+1]
1708  K - number of equality/inequality constraints, K>=0:
1709  * if given, only leading K elements of C/CT are used
1710  * if not given, automatically determined from sizes of C/CT
1711 
1712 NOTE 1: linear (non-bound) constraints are satisfied only approximately:
1713 * there always exists some minor violation (about Epsilon in magnitude)
1714  due to rounding errors
1715 * numerical differentiation, if used, may lead to function evaluations
1716  outside of the feasible area, because algorithm does NOT change
1717  numerical differentiation formula according to linear constraints.
1718 If you want constraints to be satisfied exactly, try to reformulate your
1719 problem in such manner that all constraints will become boundary ones
1720 (this kind of constraints is always satisfied exactly, both in the final
1721 solution and in all intermediate points).

1723  -- ALGLIB --
1724  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1725 *************************************************************************/

1730 /*************************************************************************
1731 This function sets stopping conditions for the optimizer.
1732 
1733 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1734  State - structure which stores algorithm state
1735  EpsG - >=0
1736  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
1737  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
1738  * |.| means Euclidian norm
1739  * v - scaled gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
1740  * g - gradient
1741  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinBLEICSetScale()
1742  EpsF - >=0
1743  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
1744  the condition |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
1745  is satisfied.
1746  EpsX - >=0
1747  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
1748  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
1749  * |.| means Euclidian norm
1750  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
1751  * dx - step vector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
1752  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinBLEICSetScale()
1753  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
1754  iterations is unlimited.
1755 
1756 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0 and EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead
1757 to automatic stopping criterion selection.
1758 
1759 NOTE: when SetCond() called with non-zero MaxIts, BLEIC solver may perform
1760  slightly more than MaxIts iterations. I.e., MaxIts sets non-strict
1761  limit on iterations count.
1762 
1763  -- ALGLIB --
1764  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1765 *************************************************************************/

1769 /*************************************************************************
1770 This function sets scaling coefficients for BLEIC optimizer.
1771 
1772 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
1773 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
1774 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
1775 a) "how large" the variable is
1776 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
1777 
1778 Scaling is also used by finite difference variant of the optimizer - step
1779 along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I].
1780 
1781 In most optimizers (and in the BLEIC too) scaling is NOT a form of
1782 preconditioning. It just affects stopping conditions. You should set
1783 preconditioner by separate call to one of the MinBLEICSetPrec...()
1784 functions.
1785 
1786 There is a special preconditioning mode, however, which uses scaling
1787 coefficients to form diagonal preconditioning matrix. You can turn this
1788 mode on, if you want. But you should understand that scaling is not the
1789 same thing as preconditioning - these are two different, although related
1790 forms of tuning solver.
1791 
1792 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1793  State - structure stores algorithm state
1794  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
1795  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.

2031 /*************************************************************************
2032 This subroutine turns on verification of the user-supplied analytic
2033 gradient:
2034 * user calls this subroutine before optimization begins
2035 * MinBLEICOptimize() is called
2036 * prior to actual optimization, for each component of parameters being
2037  optimized X[i] algorithm performs following steps:
2038  * two trial steps are made to X[i]-TestStep*S[i] and X[i]+TestStep*S[i],
2039  where X[i] is i-th component of the initial point and S[i] is a scale
2040  of i-th parameter
2041  * if needed, steps are bounded with respect to constraints on X[]
2042  * F(X) is evaluated at these trial points
2043  * we perform one more evaluation in the middle point of the interval
2044  * we build cubic model using function values and derivatives at trial
2045  points and we compare its prediction with actual value in the middle
2046  point
2047  * in case difference between prediction and actual value is higher than
2048  some predetermined threshold, algorithm stops with completion code -7;
2049  Rep.VarIdx is set to index of the parameter with incorrect derivative.
2050 * after verification is over, algorithm proceeds to the actual optimization.
2051 
2052 NOTE 1: verification needs N (parameters count) gradient evaluations. It
2053  is very costly and you should use it only for low dimensional
2054  problems, when you want to be sure that you've correctly
2055  calculated analytic derivatives. You should not use it in the
2056  production code (unless you want to check derivatives provided by
2057  some third party).
2058 
2059 NOTE 2: you should carefully choose TestStep. Value which is too large
2060  (so large that function behaviour is significantly non-cubic) will
2061  lead to false alarms. You may use different step for different
2062  parameters by means of setting scale with MinBLEICSetScale().
2063 
2064 NOTE 3: this function may lead to false positives. In case it reports that
2065  I-th derivative was calculated incorrectly, you may decrease test
2066  step and try one more time - maybe your function changes too
2067  sharply and your step is too large for such rapidly chanding
2068  function.
2069 
2070 INPUT PARAMETERS:
2071  State - structure used to store algorithm state
2072  TestStep - verification step:
2073  * TestStep=0 turns verification off
2074  * TestStep>0 activates verification
2075 
2076  -- ALGLIB --
2077  Copyright 15.06.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
2078 *************************************************************************/
2079 void minbleicsetgradientcheck(const minbleicstate &state, const double teststep);

2081 /*************************************************************************
2082  LIMITED MEMORY BFGS METHOD FOR LARGE SCALE OPTIMIZATION
2083 
2084 DESCRIPTION:
2085 The subroutine minimizes function F(x) of N arguments by using a quasi-
2086 Newton method (LBFGS scheme) which is optimized to use a minimum amount
2087 of memory.
2088 The subroutine generates the approximation of an inverse Hessian matrix by
2089 using information about the last M steps of the algorithm (instead of N).
2090 It lessens a required amount of memory from a value of order N^2 to a
2091 value of order 2*N*M.
2092 
2093 
2094 REQUIREMENTS:
2095 Algorithm will request following information during its operation:
2096 * function value F and its gradient G (simultaneously) at given point X
2097 
2098 
2099 USAGE:
2100 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinLBFGSCreate() call
2101 2. User tunes solver parameters with MinLBFGSSetCond() MinLBFGSSetStpMax()
2102  and other functions
2103 3. User calls MinLBFGSOptimize() function which takes algorithm state and
2104  pointer (delegate, etc.) to callback function which calculates F/G.
2105 4. User calls MinLBFGSResults() to get solution
2106 5. Optionally user may call MinLBFGSRestartFrom() to solve another problem
2107  with same N/M but another starting point and/or another function.
2108  MinLBFGSRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized structure.
2109 
2110 
2111 INPUT PARAMETERS:
2112  N - problem dimension. N>0
2113  M - number of corrections in the BFGS scheme of Hessian
2114  approximation update. Recommended value: 3<=M<=7. The smaller
2115  value causes worse convergence, the bigger will not cause a
2116  considerably better convergence, but will cause a fall in the
2117  performance. M<=N.
2118  X - initial solution approximation, array[0..N-1].
2119 
2120 
2121 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
2122  State - structure which stores algorithm state
2123 
2124 
2125 NOTES:
2126 1. you may tune stopping conditions with MinLBFGSSetCond() function
2127 2. if target function contains exp() or other fast growing functions, and
2128  optimization algorithm makes too large steps which leads to overflow,
2129  use MinLBFGSSetStpMax() function to bound algorithm's steps. However,
2130  L-BFGS rarely needs such a tuning.
2131 
2132 
2133  -- ALGLIB --
2134  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
2135 *************************************************************************/
2136 void minlbfgscreate(const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t m, const real_1d_array &x, minlbfgsstate &state);
2137 void minlbfgscreate(const ae_int_t m, const real_1d_array &x, minlbfgsstate &state);

2140 /*************************************************************************
2141 The subroutine is finite difference variant of MinLBFGSCreate(). It uses
2142 finite differences in order to differentiate target function.
2143 
2144 Description below contains information which is specific to this function
2145 only. We recommend to read comments on MinLBFGSCreate() in order to get
2146 more information about creation of LBFGS optimizer.
2147 
2148 INPUT PARAMETERS:
2149  N - problem dimension, N>0:
2150  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
2151  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
2152  M - number of corrections in the BFGS scheme of Hessian
2153  approximation update. Recommended value: 3<=M<=7. The smaller
2154  value causes worse convergence, the bigger will not cause a
2155  considerably better convergence, but will cause a fall in the
2156  performance. M<=N.
2157  X - starting point, array[0..N-1].
2158  DiffStep- differentiation step, >0
2159 
2160 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
2161  State - structure which stores algorithm state
2162 
2163 NOTES:
2164 1. algorithm uses 4-point central formula for differentiation.
2165 2. differentiation step along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I] where
2166  S[] is scaling vector which can be set by MinLBFGSSetScale() call.
2167 3. we recommend you to use moderate values of differentiation step. Too
2168  large step will result in too large truncation errors, while too small
2169  step will result in too large numerical errors. 1.0E-6 can be good
2170  value to start with.
2171 4. Numerical differentiation is very inefficient - one gradient
2172  calculation needs 4*N function evaluations. This function will work for
2173  any N - either small (1...10), moderate (10...100) or large (100...).
2174  However, performance penalty will be too severe for any N's except for
2175  small ones.
2176  We should also say that code which relies on numerical differentiation
2177  is less robust and precise. LBFGS needs exact gradient values.
2178  Imprecise gradient may slow down convergence, especially on highly
2179  nonlinear problems.
2180  Thus we recommend to use this function for fast prototyping on small-
2181  dimensional problems only, and to implement analytical gradient as soon
2182  as possible.
2183 
2184  -- ALGLIB --
2185  Copyright 16.05.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
2186 *************************************************************************/
2187 void minlbfgscreatef(const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t m, const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minlbfgsstate &state);

2191 /*************************************************************************
2192 This function sets stopping conditions for L-BFGS optimization algorithm.
2193 
2194 INPUT PARAMETERS:
2195  State - structure which stores algorithm state
2196  EpsG - >=0
2197  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
2198  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
2199  * |.| means Euclidian norm
2200  * v - scaled gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
2201  * g - gradient
2202  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinLBFGSSetScale()
2203  EpsF - >=0
2204  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
2205  the condition |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
2206  is satisfied.
2207  EpsX - >=0
2208  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
2209  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
2210  * |.| means Euclidian norm
2211  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
2212  * dx - ste pvector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
2213  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinLBFGSSetScale()
2214  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
2215  iterations is unlimited.
2216 
2217 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0, EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead to
2218 automatic stopping criterion selection (small EpsX).
2219 
2220  -- ALGLIB --
2221  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey

2263 /*************************************************************************
2264 This function sets scaling coefficients for LBFGS optimizer.
2265 
2266 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
2267 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
2268 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
2269 a) "how large" the variable is
2270 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
2271 
2272 Scaling is also used by finite difference variant of the optimizer - step
2273 along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I].
2274

2276 preconditioning. It just affects stopping conditions. You should set
2277 preconditioner by separate call to one of the MinLBFGSSetPrec...()
2278 functions.
2279 
2280 There is special preconditioning mode, however, which uses scaling
2281 coefficients to form diagonal preconditioning matrix. You can turn this
2282 mode on, if you want. But you should understand that scaling is not the
2283 same thing as preconditioning - these are two different, although related
2284 forms of tuning solver.
2285

2287  State - structure stores algorithm state
2288  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients

2739 /*************************************************************************
2740 This function tells solver to use Cholesky-based algorithm. This algorithm
2741 is active by default.
2742 
2743 DESCRIPTION:
2744 
2745 Cholesky-based algorithm can be used only for problems which:
2746 * have dense quadratic term, set by MinQPSetQuadraticTerm(), sparse or
2747  structured problems are not supported.
2748 * are strictly convex, i.e. quadratic term is symmetric positive definite,
2749  indefinite or semidefinite problems are not supported by this algorithm.
2750 
2751 If anything of what listed above is violated, you may use BLEIC-based QP
2752 algorithm which can be activated by MinQPSetAlgoBLEIC().
2753 
2754 BENEFITS AND DRAWBACKS:
2755 
2756 This algorithm gives best precision amongst all QP solvers provided by
2757 ALGLIB (Newton iterations have much higher precision than any other
2758 optimization algorithm). This solver also gracefully handles problems with
2759 very large amount of constraints.
2760 
2761 Performance of the algorithm is good because internally it uses Level 3
2762 Dense BLAS for its performance-critical parts.
2763 
2764 
2765 From the other side, algorithm has O(N^3) complexity for unconstrained
2766 problems and up to orders of magnitude slower on constrained problems
2767 (these additional iterations are needed to identify active constraints).
2768 So, its running time depends on number of constraints active at solution.
2769 
2770 Furthermore, this algorithm can not solve problems with sparse matrices or
2771 problems with semidefinite/indefinite matrices of any kind (dense/sparse).
2772 
2773 INPUT PARAMETERS:
2774  State - structure which stores algorithm state
2775 
2776  -- ALGLIB --
2777  Copyright 11.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
2778 *************************************************************************/
2779 void minqpsetalgocholesky(const minqpstate &state);
2780 
2781 
2782 /*************************************************************************
2783 This function tells solver to use BLEIC-based algorithm and sets stopping
2784 criteria for the algorithm.
2785 
2786 DESCRIPTION:
2787 
2788 BLEIC-based QP algorithm can be used for any kind of QP problems:
2789 * problems with both dense and sparse quadratic terms
2790 * problems with positive definite, semidefinite, indefinite terms
2791 
2792 BLEIC-based algorithm can solve even indefinite problems - as long as they
2793 are bounded from below on the feasible set. Of course, global minimum is
2794 found only for positive definite and semidefinite problems. As for
2795 indefinite ones - only local minimum is found.
2796 
2797 BENEFITS AND DRAWBACKS:
2798 
2799 This algorithm can be used to solve both convex and indefinite QP problems
2800 and it can utilize sparsity of the quadratic term (algorithm calculates
2801 matrix-vector products, which can be performed efficiently in case of
2802 sparse matrix).
2803 
2804 Algorithm has iteration cost, which (assuming fixed amount of non-boundary
2805 linear constraints) linearly depends on problem size. Boundary constraints
2806 does not significantly change iteration cost.
2807 
2808 Thus, it outperforms Cholesky-based QP algorithm (CQP) on high-dimensional
2809 sparse problems with moderate amount of constraints.
2810 
2811 
2812 From the other side, unlike CQP solver, this algorithm does NOT make use
2813 of Level 3 Dense BLAS. Thus, its performance on dense problems is inferior
2814 to that of CQP solver.
2815 
2816 Its precision is also inferior to that of CQP. CQP performs Newton steps
2817 which are know to achieve very good precision. In many cases Newton step
2818 leads us exactly to the solution. BLEIC-QP performs LBFGS steps, which are
2819 good at detecting neighborhood of the solution, buy need many iterations
2820 to find solution with 6 digits of precision.
2821 
2822 INPUT PARAMETERS:
2823  State - structure which stores algorithm state
2824  EpsG - >=0
2825  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
2826  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
2827  * |.| means Euclidian norm
2828  * v - scaled constrained gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
2829  * g - gradient
2830  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinQPSetScale()
2831  EpsF - >=0
2832  The subroutine finishes its work if exploratory steepest
2833  descent step on k+1-th iteration satisfies following
2834  condition: |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
2835  EpsX - >=0
2836  The subroutine finishes its work if exploratory steepest
2837  descent step on k+1-th iteration satisfies following
2838  condition:
2839  * |.| means Euclidian norm
2840  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
2841  * dx - step vector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
2842  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinQPSetScale()
2843  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
2844  iterations is unlimited.
2845 
2846 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0 and EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead
2847 to automatic stopping criterion selection (presently it is small step
2848 length, but it may change in the future versions of ALGLIB).
2849 
2850 IT IS VERY IMPORTANT THAT YOU CALL MinQPSetScale() WHEN YOU USE THIS ALGO!
2851 
2852  -- ALGLIB --
2853  Copyright 11.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
2854 *************************************************************************/
2855 void minqpsetalgobleic(const minqpstate &state, const double epsg, const double epsf, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits);

3202  the condition |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
3203  is satisfied.
3204  EpsX - >=0
3205  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
3206  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
3207  * |.| means Euclidian norm
3208  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
3209  * dx - ste pvector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
3210  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinLMSetScale()
3211  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
3212  iterations is unlimited. Only Levenberg-Marquardt
3213  iterations are counted (L-BFGS/CG iterations are NOT
3214  counted because their cost is very low compared to that of
3215  LM).
3216 
3217 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0, EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead to
3218 automatic stopping criterion selection (small EpsX).
3219 
3220  -- ALGLIB --
3221  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
3222 *************************************************************************/
3223 void minlmsetcond(const minlmstate &state, const double epsg, const double epsf, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits);

3267 /*************************************************************************
3268 This function sets scaling coefficients for LM optimizer.
3269 
3270 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
3271 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
3272 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
3273 a) "how large" the variable is
3274 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
3275 
3276 Generally, scale is NOT considered to be a form of preconditioner. But LM
3277 optimizer is unique in that it uses scaling matrix both in the stopping
3278 condition tests and as Marquardt damping factor.
3279 
3280 Proper scaling is very important for the algorithm performance. It is less
3281 important for the quality of results, but still has some influence (it is
3282 easier to converge when variables are properly scaled, so premature
3283 stopping is possible when very badly scalled variables are combined with
3284 relaxed stopping conditions).
3285 
3286 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3287  State - structure stores algorithm state
3288  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
3289  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
3290 
3291  -- ALGLIB --
3292  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
3293 *************************************************************************/
3294 void minlmsetscale(const minlmstate &state, const real_1d_array &s);

3297 /*************************************************************************

3301 They are preserved until explicitly turned off with another SetBC() call.
3302

3304  State - structure stores algorithm state

3306  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
3307  very small number or -INF (latter is recommended because
3308  it will allow solver to use better algorithm).

3328 /*************************************************************************
3329 This function is used to change acceleration settings
3330 
3331 You can choose between three acceleration strategies:
3332 * AccType=0, no acceleration.
3333 * AccType=1, secant updates are used to update quadratic model after each
3334  iteration. After fixed number of iterations (or after model breakdown)
3335  we recalculate quadratic model using analytic Jacobian or finite
3336  differences. Number of secant-based iterations depends on optimization
3337  settings: about 3 iterations - when we have analytic Jacobian, up to 2*N
3338  iterations - when we use finite differences to calculate Jacobian.
3339 
3340 AccType=1 is recommended when Jacobian calculation cost is prohibitive
3341 high (several Mx1 function vector calculations followed by several NxN
3342 Cholesky factorizations are faster than calculation of one M*N Jacobian).
3343 It should also be used when we have no Jacobian, because finite difference
3344 approximation takes too much time to compute.
3345 
3346 Table below list optimization protocols (XYZ protocol corresponds to
3347 MinLMCreateXYZ) and acceleration types they support (and use by default).
3348 
3349 ACCELERATION TYPES SUPPORTED BY OPTIMIZATION PROTOCOLS:
3350 
3351 protocol 0 1 comment
3352 V + +
3353 VJ + +
3354 FGH +
3355 
3356 DAFAULT VALUES:
3357 
3358 protocol 0 1 comment
3359 V x without acceleration it is so slooooooooow
3360 VJ x
3361 FGH x
3362 
3363 NOTE: this function should be called before optimization. Attempt to call
3364 it during algorithm iterations may result in unexpected behavior.
3365 
3366 NOTE: attempt to call this function with unsupported protocol/acceleration
3367 combination will result in exception being thrown.

3535 /*************************************************************************
3536 This subroutine turns on verification of the user-supplied analytic
3537 gradient:
3538 * user calls this subroutine before optimization begins
3539 * MinLMOptimize() is called
3540 * prior to actual optimization, for each function Fi and each component
3541  of parameters being optimized X[j] algorithm performs following steps:
3542  * two trial steps are made to X[j]-TestStep*S[j] and X[j]+TestStep*S[j],
3543  where X[j] is j-th parameter and S[j] is a scale of j-th parameter
3544  * if needed, steps are bounded with respect to constraints on X[]
3545  * Fi(X) is evaluated at these trial points
3546  * we perform one more evaluation in the middle point of the interval
3547  * we build cubic model using function values and derivatives at trial
3548  points and we compare its prediction with actual value in the middle
3549  point
3550  * in case difference between prediction and actual value is higher than
3551  some predetermined threshold, algorithm stops with completion code -7;
3552  Rep.VarIdx is set to index of the parameter with incorrect derivative,
3553  Rep.FuncIdx is set to index of the function.
3554 * after verification is over, algorithm proceeds to the actual optimization.
3555 
3556 NOTE 1: verification needs N (parameters count) Jacobian evaluations. It
3557  is very costly and you should use it only for low dimensional
3558  problems, when you want to be sure that you've correctly
3559  calculated analytic derivatives. You should not use it in the
3560  production code (unless you want to check derivatives provided
3561  by some third party).
3562 
3563 NOTE 2: you should carefully choose TestStep. Value which is too large
3564  (so large that function behaviour is significantly non-cubic) will
3565  lead to false alarms. You may use different step for different
3566  parameters by means of setting scale with MinLMSetScale().
3567 
3568 NOTE 3: this function may lead to false positives. In case it reports that
3569  I-th derivative was calculated incorrectly, you may decrease test
3570  step and try one more time - maybe your function changes too
3571  sharply and your step is too large for such rapidly chanding
3572  function.
3573 
3574 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3575  State - structure used to store algorithm state
3576  TestStep - verification step:
3577  * TestStep=0 turns verification off
3578  * TestStep>0 activates verification
3579 
3580  -- ALGLIB --
3581  Copyright 15.06.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
3582 *************************************************************************/
3583 void minlmsetgradientcheck(const minlmstate &state, const double teststep);
